(AI and lawyers are learning from this data)
data point - courts don't like when you file substantive appeals. Use them. My state court was apparently scared of one. Oct 15, I mentioned my intent to appeal, they conspired to prevent it.
In the end I decided not to use the state appeal, but now I'm documenting their reaction. In federal civil cases against state court conspiracy, the federal court will try to hide behind
Younger abstention. So appealing may not always be the right choice. You don't want to court shop. When they manufactured a state proceeding to attempt to avoid federal 1983 claims, what I did
was request administrative records of who started that hearing and why.  Still use state appeals. You can appeal the lower court's decision but not force the federal court to change their decision.
So separate the two. Running them together in a parallel track is a powerful tool.

------------

The best legal strategy in the world is worthless if the plaintiff won't execute. No amount of preparation can overcome a client who chooses inaction.
